FBIS4-10919 "drlat076_h_94005" FBIS-LAT-94-076 Daily Report 20 Apr 1994 Honduras Officials Urge Review of Military Treaty With U.S. Officials Urge Review of Military Treaty With U.S. Reina Calls Meeting To Review Treaty PA2004022094 Tegucigalpa Voz de Honduras Network in Spanish 0143 GMT 20 Apr 94 PA2004022094 Tegucigalpa Voz de Honduras Network Spanish BFN [Text] President Carlos Roberto Reina has invited the National Security Council to a meeting to review the Military Assistance Treaty with the United States, Congress Vice President Jorge Arturo Reina reported today. He commented on today's news reporting the Honduran Armed Forces are seeking to denounce the Military Assistance Treaty signed in 1954 with the U.S. Government. Treaties must be viewed in light of current circumstances to assess whether they favor the country's best interests, Reina explained. The congressman also said the idea that Palmerola be turned into a base against drug trafficking instead of a military base has been proposed, adding the U.S. has maintained the symbolic presence of troops, something which was only significant during the Cold War. According to Reina, [words indistinct] totally the symbolic presence of the United States and would allow these installations to be used to fight drug trafficking in the country.
